<div id="review_1696265642" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1696265642" />
    <a title="Sjervey" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/46402296-sjervey"><img alt="Sjervey" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/u_50x66-632230dc9882b4352d753eedf9396530.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1696265642?book_show_action=true">Jan 12, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Sjervey" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Sjervey" href="/user/show/46402296-sjervey">Sjervey</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/18963942-a-brief-account-of-the-destruction-of-the-indies-or-a-faithful-narrativ">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1696265642" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3705579655492509451">This book is essentially a catalog of atrocities allegedly committed by the conquistadors that invaded the new world under the aegis of the Spanish government. I say allegedly but I do not mean to imply that atrocities did not occur. They certainly did. It;s just that there is a degree of repetition in this book tht makes me wonder what Bishop de las Casas agenda was in writing it. WHo was his intended audience? What his hoped for result? I haven&apos;t researched that and I feel it should be before </span>
  <span id="freeText3705579655492509451" style="display:none">This book is essentially a catalog of atrocities allegedly committed by the conquistadors that invaded the new world under the aegis of the Spanish government. I say allegedly but I do not mean to imply that atrocities did not occur. They certainly did. It;s just that there is a degree of repetition in this book tht makes me wonder what Bishop de las Casas agenda was in writing it. WHo was his intended audience? What his hoped for result? I haven't researched that and I feel it should be before one accepts everything in this book at face value. Nevertheless, the Bishop must have been confident that enough of it was true so that it would be accepted in making his point, whatever that was. One thing I can say, I read the whole book hoping it would not be simply repetition after repetition of atrocity after atrocity, but I was disappointed. That's all the book amounts to. </span>
